@book{leroy_behavioral_2011,
	title = {Behavioral {Integrity} {Regarding} {Safety}},
	abstract = {Literature on safety climate suggests that work-related accidents are prevented in an environment that both adheres to safety regulations and responds constructively to errors. Research has yet to clarify however how leaders combine the seemingly paradoxical aspects of enforcing safety regulations while allowing room for mistakes against safety regulations. We use theory and research on behavioral integrity to hypothesize that when leaders are perceived to live up to espoused safety values, teams are more likely to place a higher priority on safety regulations and feel more psychologically safe to speak up and admit mistakes. Results from survey data of 580 nurses and 54 teams showed that head nurse behavioral integrity for safety positively relates to team priority of safety and team psychological safety. In turn, team priority of safety and psychological safety were found to be respectively negatively and positively related with the number of treatment errors reported to head nurses. We further demonstrated an interaction effect between team priority of safety and team psychological safety on reported errors such that the relationship between team priority of safety and the number of errors was stronger for higher levels of team psychological safety. Finally we showed that team priority of safety, psychological safety, and their interaction mediated the relation between behavioral integrity for safety and reported treatment errors. We discuss how these results offer more insight into how behavioral integrity helps solve the managerial dilemma of providing clear direction while allowing room for employee learning. Keywords: Behavioral integrity, priority of safety, psychological safety, treatment errors, safety climate, leadership.},
